@{U}1.1  About the Tera Desktop                                   TeraDesk@{u}  
  
Tera Desktop (TeraDesk) is a replacement for the ST, STE or TT desktop. 
It provides more facilities than the built-in TOS desktops (especially  
the ones in TOS versions 1.*). 
  
TeraDesk is currently the only open-souce desktop available for 16-bit
and 32-bit  Atari computers.  Developers' goal has  been  to  maintain 
TeraDesk as a small, simple, fast and reliable desktop, which would be 
functional in the  modern multitasking  environments and  all flavours 
and versions of TOS-compatible operating  system(s),  and yet to keep, 
as much as reasonable, familiarity with the original TOS desktop. 

TeraDesk is NOT intended  to be a direct replacement for the excellent 
but  resources-demanding desktops like  Thing or Jinnee,  but  instead
is designed to be used  where  disk space or  system memory  and speed 
limitations (or price) make the use of those fine desktops impractical
(e.g. TeraDesk's  size and memory usage is currently only about 1/3 to 
1/2 of Jinnee's in a similar setup). 

TeraDesk  was  initially  developed  by  Wout Klaren. Version 1.41 was  
released in 1994 and here the development stopped for some time.  
  
Version  1.42 was the first one published (in the year 2002) under the  
GPL.  
  
Version 2.0  was an  adaptation by Henk Robbers  to modern AES's (like  
N.AES,  XaAES  & MagiC).

Version  2.3  was  the first result of joined efforts  of Henk Robbers
and  Djordje Vukovic, comprising a number of new features.  
  
Versions  3.* are the result of continued cooperation of H.Robbers and  
Dj.Vukovic;  they are a significant  further improvement of TeraDesk's  
functionality, the program having undergone an extensive redesign.  
  
  
The program may  be  copied and distributed freely  provided  that the 
terms of the GPL (see accompanying file COPYING) are respected. If the  
program is  distributed  by a PD library,  only the  costs of the disk
and distribution may be recovered.  
  
Tera Desktop files (included in the binary distribution) are:  
  
             COPYING          Copy of the GPL  
             DESKTOP.PRG      The Tera Desktop program  
             DESKTOS.PRG      Reduced version for single TOS only  
             DESKTOP.RSC      English resource file  
             DESKTOP.RSD      English resource definitions file  
             ICONS.RSC        Monochrome icons resource file  
             CICONS.RSC       Colour icons resource file  
             README.TXT       Introduction in English  
             HIST_V3.TXT      Development history in English  
             TERADESK.HYP     ST-Guide manual in English  
             TERADESK.REF     Reference file for the above  
             TERADESK.INF     Sample configuration file 
             TERADESK.PAL     Sample palette file 

There also exists  a source distribution  which contains  the complete
source tree of TeraDesk, to be compiled and linked with PureC 1.1
 
@endnode  
  
  
