@{U}1.2.3 Screen resolutions                                      TeraDesk@{u}  
  
It  is  recommended that you use Tera Desktop in high or medium screen  
resolution.  When  used  in  low (ST-low) resolution, it may work with  
some   restrictions,   depending   on  TOS  version,  because  of  the  
limitation  (imposed by the older versions of the AES)  on the size of 
menus (small screen buffer size).  This limitation  is met by removing 
some menu items when insufficient screen buffer size is detected (this 
should never happen EXCEPT in ST-low and ST-medium resolution):  
  
- In TOS 1.04 and older, menu separator bars are removed;  
  
- In TOS 1.02 and older, some menu items are removed, i.e:  
  
       -Delete...    
       -Print...   
       -View unsorted
       -Reverse order   
       -Copy disk...   
       -Show size   
       -Show date    
       -Show time    
       -Show attributes   
       -Set program types...   
       -Window options...   
       -Video options...   
       -Save as...  
       
Configuration items set by removed menu items  can still be set in the
configuration  file.  These  options  are  also  still  available  via 
Keyboard shortcuts. See also Desk preferences...      
   
In ST-High resolution there should not be any problems related to menu 
size in any old TOS version. See also TOS Version compatibility.  
  
If  TeraDesk  is to be used exclusively in high screen resolutions and  
long-file-names-capable   environment,   length   of   the  scrollable  
filename  and   pathname  fields   (see  Scrolled text fields)  can be  
increased  in  the  dialogs.  TeraDesk uses these fields in such a way  
that  it is  safe to use a resource editor and  increase the widths of  
the  relevant  dialogs  and  scrollable  fields,  until  they suit the  
user's  esthetic  and  other requirements.  Note that lengths of other  
alphanumeric  editable fields (i.e. filetype masks and search strings)  
should NOT be changed.

Screen resolution can be changed, depending on the AES and TOS version
used, through Video options... dialog.  This  feature does not work in
some AESses though; generally, it is effective only with some versions
of AES 4. 
 
  
@endnode  
  
  
