@{U}2  Installation                                               TeraDesk@{u}  
  
Tera Desktop should be installed as follows:  
  
1. Create  a  folder called e.g. DESKTOP or TERADESK  anywhere on your  
floppy or hard disk  (or in a RAM disk) to hold Tera Desktop files. It
is also possible, although a bit untidy,  to put Tera Desktop into the
root directory of a disk volume.   

2. Copy into this folder the files:  
  
       DESKTOP.PRG  (if  you  intend  to use multitasking)  OR   
       DESKTOS.PRG  (if you  will  work  in  Single-TOS  only)    
       DESKTOP.RSC    
       ICONS.RSC    (if you will use monochrome icons) AND/OR  
       CICONS.PRG   (if your AES can support colour icons)   
  
Note  that  DESKTOP.PRG  will  work in single-TOS as well; DESKTOS.PRG  
just  saves  a  few  kilobytes of memory  by not containing code which 
is not relevant in  Single-TOS environment,  and by  having a somewhat 
limited support for the AV-protocol  (this limitation  is imposed only
for the sake of smaller program size).

If only DESKTOS.PRG is  to be used,  it may be renamed to  DESKTOP.PRG 
after copying,  but this is required only if  AV-protocol clients will 
be used.
  
You can  (but need not) also copy  into this folder  the configuration 
files TERADESK.INF and  TERADESK.PAL  from the  \EXAMPLES folder. Note
that these files  are set  for one particular computer  configuration, 
and may not  be appropriate for your setup  (Tera Desktop will attempt 
to  obey all that is  specified  in the configuration file,  no matter 
what the  actual  environment is,  e.g. the example  TERADESK.INF  has 
desktop icon for drives  A, B and C only,  and, if  that file is used, 
only those disk icons will be shown on the desktop).  Of course, these
files can be adjusted to any user's particular environment by defining
additional desktop and window icons, filetypes, applications, etc.

If you would feel more comfortable with  Tera Desktop  translated into 
some other language, you can replace DESKTOP.RSC  (and maybe ICONS.RSC 
and  CICONS.RSC)  with  translated  ones.  All text  strings  used  by 
Tera Desktop are located in DESKTOP.RSC  (except default filenames and 
a warning that DESKTOP.RSC can not be found).  It is thus possible  to 
completely  adapt Tera Desktop  to other languages by using translated
resource  files. Check the links on  Tera Desktop's home web page  for 
currently available translation(s).
  
3. If  you  use   ST-GUIDE,  copy  TERADESK.HYP and TERADESK.REF  from
the \DOC folder to the folder where your other .HYP files are.  If you
would like a translated  hypertext manual instead,  check the links on 
Tera Desktop's home web page for currently available translations, and
replace the English TERADESK.HYP and TERADESK.REF with translated ones
if they exist.
  
4. ONLY if you want  to convert  TeraDesk V2.*  configuration files to 
the new format of TeraDesk V3, you need to get also CFG2INF.PRG;  This  
utility  (not  included in  the  binary  distribution  but   available 
separately)  is basically a  tweaked compilation  of the  Tera Desktop 
itself, with  the  capability to read  only the old file format and to
write  only the new  format-  hence  an inappropriately large size  of
CFG2INF.PRG;  use it  only  to convert your old *.CFG files (use first  
Load Settings...  then  Save Settings as...), and  then promptly  dump  
it  to the trash bin. The created  .INF file  will have  the format of
TeraDesk 3.0 and there will be a couple  of warnings about  some minor
differences when it is read by a newer version of TeraDesk. 

See also Configuration files for more details.  
  
CFG2INF.PRG utility is not supported by the source code after TeraDesk 
Version 3.01.
  
After copying the necessary files, Tera Desktop can now  be started in 
the usual way by double clicking on its name.  

5.  Cooperation of Tera Desktop  with some other applications  will be
improved if it is announced  that certain protocols can be handled. In
order to do so, the following environment variables can be defined:

 AVSERVER=DESKTOP
 FONTSELECT=DESKTOP
 
These declare  TeraDesk as the AV-Server (see The AV Protocol)  and as
the font-selector (see The FONT Protocol). In Single-TOS configuration
these protocols can be used by some accessories (such as ST-Guide); in
multitasking configurations they can be used  by concurrently  running
applications. See also Supported Protocols.

The manner of declaration of environment variables depends on variants 
of the OS and utilities used.
  
6. It is convenient to set TeraDesk to start automatically  at  system
boot. If you have TOS version 1.04 (also known as TOS 1.4)  or higher, 
you can set it up for that by  installing TeraDesk  as  an application
and changing its boot status from 'Normal' to 'Auto'. Remember to save
desktop configuration after this.  As from now on TeraDesk  will  take 
over all desktop tasks, prior to saving the desktop configuration  all
other applications  should be deinstalled,  all unneeded icons removed 
from the desktop and all windows closed. This is not required but will 
reduce  the size of  DESKTOP.INF  (or NEWDESK.INF)  and will also free 
some memory. 
  
If  you  have  TOS version 1.0 or 1.02  you must use a program such as  
STARTGEM to run DESKTOP from an AUTO folder.  
  
If  you  use  Atari  AES 4.1,  you  can  put  something similar to the  
following directive into your GEM.CNF file:  
    
 shell path\to\TeraDesk\desktop.prg  
  
Then,  the  built-in desktop of AES 4.1 will  not be loaded at startup  
and  TeraDesk  will  run  as  the  desktop  instead. Beside being more  
elegant,  this  also  saves  some  memory.

If you use Geneva, N.AES, XaAES or MyAES,  you should in a similar way 
specify TeraDesk as the default shell in the appropriate places in the  
configuration files  of these  AESses  (i.e. in   GEM.CNF,  N_AES.CNF,
XA_EXEC.SCL and MYAES.CNF respectively). 
    
If  you  use  MagiC,  TeraDesk  should be specified as a shell via the  
#_SHL directive in MAGX.INF, as something similar to:

 #_SHL PATH\TO\TERADESK\DESKTOP.PRG 
  
7. Some versions of AES (e.g. Geneva 4) declare themselves  as capable
of handling colour  icons, but that capability  doesn't seem  to work. 
In such cases,  CICONS.RSC  file should be removed, and  TeraDesk will 
fall back to  monochrome icons.  Colour icons file can also be removed 
in other  environments  if there  is a need  to preserve  as much free 
memory as possible.

8. The icon files supplied contain basic sets of icons only.  Users can 
add icons at will, or use other icon files (for example, one can rename 
DESKICON.RSC and/or  DESKCICN.RSC  used  by the built-in desktop of TOS 
to ICONS.RSC and CICONS.RSC respectively, and use them with TeraDesk).

TeraDesk, since  V2.0, handles icons by name, not by index. Icons with 
the following names (or their translated equivalents) should always be 
present in the icons resource file(s):

 FLOPPY, HARD DISC, TRASH, PRINTER, FOLDER, FILE, APP

9. Some  aspects of  Tera Desktop  can be  (or may be  in the  future)
controlled through the environment variable TERAENV.  Its value should
consist of uppercase-letter flags. Currently only flag 'D' is used, as 
in:

 TERAENV=D

which to some extent controls the visual appearance of dialog objects.
See Rendering of dialog objects. 
 
@endnode  
  
  
