@{U}4.14 Scrolled text fields                                     TeraDesk@{u}  
  
In  manu  cases it is needed to enter a long text (usually a path or a 
long  filename)  into a dialog  text field. However, practical  length 
of  a  dialog  text  field  is  limited  by  dialog  size  and  screen 
resolution. 
  
To  overcome  this  difficulty a new object type has been implemented: 
input  field which is able to receive more characters then can be made 
visible.  Whether  parts of the text are invisible is indicated by the 
characters  '<' and '>' appearing around the field. Use the [Left] and 
[Right]  cursor  keys  to scroll back and forth in the fields. In this 
way names of up to about 130 characters can be entered. 
  
Pressing the [Insert] key while the cursor is in a scrolled text field   
opens the file-selector. Selected file or folder name is inserted into   
the field at cursor position.  
  
Dialog  fields  referring  to  file  names  will  have  a  8+3 form if 
TeraDesk  is  run  in  an environment which does not support long file 
names.  In  the  opposite  case  (i.e. if Mint or MagiC are detected), 
filename forms will be longer and of the scrolled text field type. 
  
Scrolled-text fields appear in the following dialogs:  
  
    Open...  
    Info...  
    New... 
    Search...  
    Set applications...  
    The command line dialog
    The name conflict dialog  
      
@endnode  
  

@node "Rendering of dialog objects"  
@image udo_fo.img 1  
   Contents  
@image udo_fo.img 4  
      Menus and Dialogs  
      
@{U}4.15 Rendering of dialog objects                              TeraDesk@{u}  
      
Some object types  in  TeraDesk  dialogs,  such as the  circular radio 
buttons, the checkbox buttons, titled frames,  buttons with underlined 
text, etc. are only supported by some versions of the AES. In order to
display  them on the screen,  the  following approach  is adopted:  An
inquiry is made  to the AES whether WHITEBAK flag in the resource file
is supported;  if it is, TeraDesk  assumes that the  AES can  draw all 
those  objects, and  lets  the AES do that.  In  the   opposite  case,
TeraDesk  draws the objects. A positive side of this approach is  that
the appearance of those objects in TeraDesk  is in  style with objects
drawn  by  the  AES in  other applications.  A negative  side  is that
some objects  drawn by some AESses look uglier than they  would be had
TeraDesk drawn  them.  Another  drawback  is  that  e.g. Geneva  marks 
relevant objects  in  a different  way  than e.g. Magic or N.AES; that
is not recognized by TeraDesk and so these capabilities of  Geneva are 
left unused.

Behaviour of TeraDesk can be controlled in this matter through the use
of  TERAENV environment variable.  If it contains character 'D' (as in
'Draw'),  TeraDesk will draw  these extended object types,  regardless
of whether an AES supports  them.   See also: Installation
      
@endnode      

  
  
